  "prompt": "What are your favorite YA novels?",
  "response": "Okay, this is a tough one, because my taste in YA is all over the place! But here are some of my favorites, broken down by categories, with a little explanation of why I love them:\n\n**Contemporary/Realistic:**\n\n*   **\"The Hate U Give\" by Angie Thomas:** This book is powerful, important, and beautifully written. Starr's journey through grief, anger, and finding her voice is incredibly compelling and relevant.\n*   **\"Eleanor & Park\" by Rainbow Rowell:** A sweet and poignant story about first love and finding acceptance. Rowell's writing is just gorgeous, and the characters are so well-developed.\n*   **\"Simon vs. the Homo Sapiens Agenda\" by Becky Albertalli:** A charming and funny coming-of-age story about a gay teenager struggling with his identity. It's heartwarming, relatable, and ultimately optimistic.\n*   **\"I'll Give You the Sun\" by Jandy Nelson:** This book is lyrically written, emotionally complex, and just plain beautiful. The story of twins Noah and Jude, torn apart by tragedy, is both heartbreaking and hopeful.\n*   **\"Everything, Everything\" by Nicola Yoon:** A sweet and compelling romance with an interesting premise - a girl with a rare disease that keeps her trapped inside.\n\n**Fantasy/Sci-Fi:**\n\n*   **\"The Hunger Games\" by Suzanne Collins:** A classic for a reason. The world-building is fantastic, and Katniss Everdeen is an iconic heroine. Plus, it sparked my love for dystopian novels!\n*   **\"Six of Crows\" by Leigh Bardugo:** This book is a masterclass in character development and plot twists. The ensemble cast is diverse and compelling, and the world-building is rich and immersive. I love the heist aspect!\n*   **\"The Cruel Prince (The Folk of the Air)\" by Holly Black:** This is a captivating fantasy series filled with fae politics, betrayals, and a strong-willed protagonist. Jude is a complex and flawed character you can't help but root for.\n*   **\"An Ember in the Ashes\" by Sabaa Tahir:** A thrilling and romantic fantasy set in a brutal, Roman-inspired empire. The dual perspectives of Laia and Elias are incredibly engaging.\n*   **\"Children of Blood and Bone\" by Tomi Adeyemi:** A vibrant and powerful fantasy inspired by West African mythology. The magic system is fascinating, and the themes of oppression and resistance are incredibly relevant.\n\n**Historical Fiction:**\n\n*   **\"The Book Thief\" by Markus Zusak:** Narrated by Death, this book is both heartbreaking and beautiful. The story of Liesel Meminger during World War II is unforgettable. (Technically can be argued if this is YA, but I read it as YA and I love it!)\n*   **\"Code Name Verity\" by Elizabeth Wein:** A gripping and suspenseful story about two female spies during World War II. The friendship between Maddie and Julie is the heart of the book.\n\n**Things I consider when choosing a book:**\n\n*   **Relatable Characters:** I want to connect with the characters and root for them.\n*   **Compelling Plot:** I need a story that will keep me engaged from beginning to end.\n*   **Meaningful Themes:** I appreciate books that explore important themes like identity, family, love, and loss.\n*   **Beautiful Writing:** Lyrical prose can elevate a story and make it truly memorable.\n\n**Important Note:** This is just a small selection, and my favorites change all the time! There are so many amazing YA books out there, and I'm always looking for new recommendations.\n\nI hope this gives you a good starting point!  What are some of your favorite YA novels? I'd love to hear them!\n",
